----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”€ What is Control Flow?

**Control flow** decides **how and when code executes** based on conditions.

ğŸ“Œ It helps JavaScript:

* Make decisions
* Repeat tasks
* Handle different scenarios

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”¹ Conditional Statements

âœ… if Statement

Executes code **only if condition is true**.

```js
let age = 20;

if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("Eligible to vote");
}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” if-else Statement

Runs one block if condition is true, otherwise another.

```js
if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("Adult");
} else {
  console.log("Minor");
}
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”‚ if-else if-else Ladder

Used for **multiple conditions**.

```js
let marks = 85;

if (marks >= 90) {
  console.log("Grade A");
} else if (marks >= 75) {
  console.log("Grade B");
} else {
  console.log("Grade C");
}
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”€ switch Statement

Used when comparing **one value with many cases**.

```js
let day = 3;

switch (day) {
  case 1:
    console.log("Monday");
    break;
  case 2:
    console.log("Tuesday");
    break;
  case 3:
    console.log("Wednesday");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Invalid day");
}
```

ğŸ“Œ `break` stops execution
ğŸ“Œ `default` runs if no case matches

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” Loops in JavaScript

Loops are used to **repeat code** until a condition is met.

---

ğŸ”„ for Loop

Best when number of iterations is known.

```js
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  console.log(i);
}
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”„ while Loop

Runs while condition is true.

```js
let i = 1;

while (i <= 3) {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”„ do-while Loop

Runs **at least once**, even if condition is false.

```js
let i = 1;

do {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
} while (i <= 2);
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” Loop Control Statements

ğŸ”¹ break

Stops loop immediately.

```js
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  if (i === 3) break;
  console.log(i);
}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”¹ continue

Skips current iteration.

```js
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  if (i === 3) continue;
  console.log(i);
}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” Special Loops (Intro)

forâ€¦of (Arrays)

```js
let skills = ["HTML", "CSS", "JS"];

for (let skill of skills) {
  console.log(skill);
}
```

---

forâ€¦in (Objects)

```js
let user = { name: "Saakshi", age: 21 };

for (let key in user) {
  console.log(key, user[key]);
}
```
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš ï¸ Infinite Loop (Avoid âŒ)

Occurs when condition never becomes false.

```js
while (true) {
  console.log("Infinite");
}
```
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âŒ Common Beginner Mistakes

* Forgetting `break` in switch
* Infinite loops
* Wrong loop condition
* Using `==` instead of `===`

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ’¡ Best Practices

* Use `switch` for fixed values
* Prefer `for` loop when count is known
* Keep conditions simple
* Test edge cases

